-- ── Dawarich ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Open-source, self-hostable alternative to Google Timeline that lets you import, visualize, and permanently own your personal location history.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2024, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Dawarich: Self-Hosted Google Timeline Alternative$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Dawarich is an open-source, self-hosted alternative to Google Timeline for owning, visualizing, and analyzing your personal location history data.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Dawarich is an open-source, self-hostable location history and personal tracking application built as a direct alternative to Google's Timeline (formerly Google Location History) feature, which Google has progressively restricted and moved on-device in recent years. The project was created by developer Evgenii Burmakin, who goes by the handle Freika on GitHub, and the name is derived from the German phrase 'da war ich,' meaning 'I was there.' Dawarich lets users import historical location data from Google Takeout exports, OwnTracks, GPX files, and other common formats, or stream live location updates from GPS-logging mobile apps such as OwnTracks, Overland, and GPSLogger, storing everything on infrastructure the user fully controls rather than on a third-party cloud service. The application is built with Ruby on Rails, uses a PostgreSQL database with the PostGIS spatial extension for geographic queries, and runs background processing with Sidekiq, and it is distributed as a Docker Compose stack that most self-hosters can deploy in a few commands, typically exposing a web interface on port 3000. Since its public release, the project has grown quickly within the self-hosting and homelab community, surpassing 9,000 stars on GitHub and building an active Discord community of several hundred members, reflecting strong demand for privacy-respecting alternatives to Big Tech location tracking as Google has scaled back Timeline's cloud backup and web-based history features. Dawarich's core product experience centers on an interactive map with multiple visualization modes, including heatmaps of visited areas and a distinctive 'Fog of War' mode that reveals only the parts of the map a user has actually visited, gradually 'uncovering' their personal travel history the way a strategy video game reveals a hidden map. Beyond visualization, Dawarich provides statistics on distance traveled, countries and cities visited, and time spent in different places, along with the ability to tag, export, and query historical trips. The software is licensed under the GNU Affero General Public License version 3 (AGPL-3.0), a strong copyleft license that permits unrestricted internal or personal self-hosted use for free, but requires anyone who modifies Dawarich and offers it as a network service (i.e., runs it as a SaaS product for others) to release their modified source code as well -- a common choice for open-source projects that want to prevent commercial clouds from freeriding on the codebase without contributing back. Commercially, the Dawarich team monetizes through Dawarich Cloud, a managed hosting option for users who want the convenience of a hosted instance without running their own server; Dawarich Cloud is offered on a Lite plan billed annually at roughly EUR 49.99 per year and a Pro plan billed monthly at roughly EUR 17.99 per month, both of which include a free trial period (commonly cited as seven days) and a risk-free refund window (around fourteen days). Dawarich Cloud infrastructure is described as encrypted in transit and at rest and hosted in European data centers with GDPR compliance, which matters to privacy-conscious users who want managed convenience without giving up data-protection guarantees. The self-hosted, free tier includes essentially the full feature set with no artificial paywall, which differentiates Dawarich from many 'open-core' projects that gate advanced functionality behind a commercial license; instead, the paid Cloud offering is purely about outsourcing infrastructure operations, not about unlocking capability. Dawarich's target users are privacy-minded individuals, self-hosting enthusiasts, and homelab operators who already run other self-hosted services (in the same spirit as Immich for photos, Nextcloud for files, or Home Assistant for smart-home data) and want the same data-ownership model applied to their location history. It is frequently discussed alongside other Google Timeline alternatives and self-hosted geo-tracking tools, and its most direct competitors include OwnTracks' own recorder component, Traccar, PhotoPrism/Immich's location features (which handle photo geodata but not continuous tracking), and various closed-source personal analytics apps; Dawarich differentiates itself by focusing specifically and comprehensively on the Google Timeline replacement use case, including first-class Google Takeout import so users migrating away from Google do not lose years of accumulated history. Deployment options extend beyond a personal server to platforms like AWS Marketplace, ElfHosted (a managed self-hosting service for open-source apps), and other Docker-friendly hosts, lowering the technical barrier for less experienced users. Because Dawarich is a young project (the team celebrated its first anniversary through a blog post, indicating the software became broadly available in roughly 2024), company-level details such as employee count, formal incorporation, or headquarters are not publicly disclosed; it operates more like an independent open-source project with a commercial cloud add-on than a traditional venture-backed company. Notable facts include its rapid GitHub star growth, an actively maintained companion project called Dawarich Atlas for offline self-hosted maps, and ongoing feature development driven heavily by community feedback via GitHub issues and Discord, all of which position Dawarich as one of the most prominent tools in the growing 'digital sovereignty' movement around personal location data.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '5b11a993-2f55-40d0-abfa-c3ac9710bd48';

