-- ── Daylite ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Native Mac, iPhone, and iPad CRM and project management app from Marketcircle for small businesses managing sales pipelines, projects, and client relationships.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$25/user/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1999, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$11-50 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Markham, Ontario, Canada$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Daylite: Mac & iOS CRM by Marketcircle$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Daylite is a native Mac, iPhone, and iPad CRM from Marketcircle that helps small businesses manage contacts, sales pipelines, and projects.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Daylite is a customer relationship management (CRM) and project management application built exclusively for Apple's ecosystem -- Mac, iPhone, and iPad -- by Marketcircle, a Canadian software company headquartered in Markham, Ontario, in the Greater Toronto Area. Marketcircle was founded in 1999, and Daylite itself launched as a breakthrough product for the original Mac OS X platform in 2002, making it one of the longest-running CRM products purpose-built for Apple hardware, at a time when most CRM vendors treated Mac support as an afterthought behind Windows and web clients. For over a decade Daylite was sold as a licensed, self-hosted product where customers ran their own sync server, but in 2015 Marketcircle launched Daylite Cloud, a hosted subscription version, and the company has since fully transitioned to a SaaS business model, discontinuing new sales of the legacy self-hosted license in favor of Daylite Cloud exclusively. Marketcircle is a small, privately held company with an estimated 11 to 50 employees, focused entirely on the Daylite product line rather than a broad portfolio, which allows it to maintain deep, native-quality integration with Apple's platforms rather than building a generic cross-platform web app. Architecturally, Daylite is a true native application built with Apple's frameworks rather than an Electron wrapper or a responsive website, which gives it tight integration with system-level features: it syncs and works alongside Apple Mail, Contacts, and Calendars, supports drag-and-drop linking of emails and files to CRM records, and offers full offline capability on Mac and iOS devices so users can view and edit records without an internet connection, with changes syncing once connectivity returns. Feature areas include contact and company management, opportunity and sales pipeline tracking, project and task management with customizable pipelines, calendaring and appointment scheduling, email integration, and reporting, positioning Daylite as an all-in-one operations hub for small businesses and professional services firms rather than a narrow point solution. Pricing is tiered by feature depth: the entry CRM plan starts at roughly $25 per user per month, a Sales and Projects plan sits around $40 per user per month, and a top Business plan runs about $55 per user per month, with all tiers backed by a 30-day free trial and Marketcircle periodically offering a 25% discount on the first 12 months for customers who choose monthly billing over annual commitment. Because Daylite is Apple-only, it deliberately does not target Windows or Android-first organizations; this narrows its addressable market but also means Daylite does not have to compromise depth of Apple integration to support other platforms, which is precisely the value proposition that keeps its loyal customer base -- many of whom are creative agencies, consultancies, financial advisors, real estate teams, and other Mac-centric small businesses -- from switching to larger, platform-agnostic CRMs. Its most direct competitors are general-purpose CRMs like HubSpot, Pipedrive, Zoho CRM, and Salesforce Essentials, none of which offer the same level of native macOS/iOS integration, offline functionality, or tight coupling with Apple Mail and Calendar; Daylite's pitch to prospective customers is explicitly built around this differentiation, positioning itself as the CRM 'made for Mac' rather than a web app that happens to run in a Mac browser. Within the Apple-focused CRM niche specifically, Daylite competes with smaller players such as OmniFocus (project management only, not full CRM) and various niche Mac-only business tools, but it holds a leading position as one of the most mature, feature-complete CRM options built specifically for the platform. Daylite is distributed through the Mac App Store as well as directly from Marketcircle's website, and the company also operates a certified consultant and reseller network (independent firms such as Daylite Mac and various regional partners) that provide implementation, customization, and training services -- a go-to-market model more typical of enterprise software than typical self-serve SaaS, reflecting the relatively high-touch, small-business-services customer base Daylite serves. Reviews on platforms like Capterra, G2, and Software Advice generally praise Daylite's Apple integration, ease of use for existing Mac users, and offline reliability, while noting common critiques such as a steeper learning curve for teams unfamiliar with CRM concepts, the platform lock-in to Apple devices, and pricing that can add up for larger teams compared to some web-first competitors. Marketcircle has received industry recognition over the years as an Apple-ecosystem software vendor and has built its reputation almost entirely around Daylite rather than a diversified product suite, giving the company a narrow but deep focus that long-tenured customers frequently cite as a reason for loyalty, since updates and support are dedicated entirely to making the one product work as well as possible on Apple hardware. Marketcircle has publicly described its shift to Daylite Cloud as a full embrace of the SaaS business model, framing the move away from self-hosted licenses as a way to deliver continuous updates, more reliable cross-device sync, and simpler onboarding than the older server-based deployment ever allowed. The company also maintains an active customer community and knowledge base, publishes regular product webinars and training resources for new Daylite Cloud subscribers, and works with independent Daylite consultants who specialize in migrating small businesses from spreadsheets, generic CRMs, or the discontinued self-hosted Daylite license onto the current cloud platform.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '27104aee-384b-47e0-8d77-8ae9c9dbfe01';

