-- ── dbt Cloud ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Managed SaaS platform from dbt Labs for building, testing, orchestrating, and documenting SQL-based data transformations using the open-source dbt framework.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2016, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$900-1,200 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$dbt Cloud: Managed Data Transformation Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$dbt Cloud is dbt Labs' managed SaaS platform for building, testing, scheduling, and documenting SQL-based data transformation pipelines at scale.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$dbt Cloud is the managed, commercial SaaS platform built by dbt Labs around the open-source dbt (data build tool) framework, which has become one of the most widely adopted standards in the modern data stack for transforming raw data inside a cloud data warehouse using SQL and version-controlled software engineering practices. dbt Labs traces its origins to Fishtown Analytics, a data consultancy founded in Philadelphia in 2016 by Tristan Handy, Drew Banin, and Connor McArthur, former colleagues at RJMetrics who built dbt internally to solve their own consulting clients' data transformation problems before open-sourcing it and eventually rebranding the company as dbt Labs to reflect the product's centrality to the business. The company has raised a total of roughly $414 million across multiple funding rounds, most notably a $222 million Series D in February 2022 led by Altimeter Capital that valued the company at $4.2 billion, with participation from Andreessen Horowitz, Sequoia, Amplify Partners, and strategic investors including Databricks, Snowflake, and Salesforce Ventures -- an unusual lineup that reflects dbt's position as connective-tissue infrastructure sitting on top of, rather than competing with, the major cloud data warehouses. dbt Labs remains headquartered in Philadelphia with a largely remote workforce distributed across North America and Europe, and as of 2026 has grown to somewhere between roughly 900 and 1,160 employees depending on the data source consulted. Architecturally, dbt's core idea is to let analytics engineers write data transformations as modular SQL SELECT statements (with Jinja templating for reusability) that dbt compiles and executes directly inside the warehouse -- an approach often summarized as the 'T' in ELT (extract, load, transform) -- rather than requiring a separate transformation engine or ETL tool; dbt handles dependency resolution between models, automated testing of data quality assumptions, auto-generated documentation, and lineage graphs showing how data flows from raw sources through to final business-ready tables. dbt Core, the underlying open-source command-line engine, is free and can be run by anyone locally or via their own orchestration; dbt Cloud is the layer dbt Labs sells commercially on top of that, adding a browser-based integrated development environment, managed job scheduling and orchestration, CI/CD workflows that automatically test code changes before merging, the dbt Semantic Layer for defining reusable business metrics, dbt Copilot (AI-assisted development for writing and debugging transformation code), and enterprise governance features such as role-based access control (RBAC) and single sign-on (SSO). Pricing for dbt Cloud is structured around a free Developer plan intended for individual use, which is capped at a monthly model-build limit (historically around 3,000 successful model builds) after which scheduled runs pause until the next cycle or an upgrade; a Starter plan priced at roughly $100 per developer seat per month with usage-based overage billing once a higher threshold of model builds (around 15,000) is exceeded; and custom-priced Enterprise and Enterprise+ tiers for organizations that need stronger governance, advanced security and connectivity controls, dedicated support, and platform-scale features. This pricing structure -- blending per-seat licensing with usage-based compute consumption tied to how many transformation jobs actually run -- makes total cost of ownership less predictable than simple flat per-seat SaaS pricing, and third-party pricing guides note that total dbt Cloud spend depends heavily on how many active developers a team has, how frequently jobs are scheduled, and which advanced features (Semantic Layer, Copilot, multi-environment CI) are enabled. dbt Cloud's target users are analytics engineers, data engineers, and data teams inside organizations that have already adopted a cloud data warehouse such as Snowflake, BigQuery, Databricks, Redshift, or Microsoft Fabric, and want to apply software engineering discipline -- version control, testing, code review, modular reuse -- to their SQL transformation logic instead of relying on ad hoc scripts or opaque BI-tool-level calculations. Because dbt has become something close to a de facto standard for the 'transform' layer of the modern data stack, dbt Cloud's competitive landscape includes both platform-native competitors bundled inside a warehouse or BI tool (such as Databricks' own workflow orchestration or Microsoft Fabric's dataflows) and independent alternatives that have emerged specifically to compete with or complement dbt Cloud, including SQLMesh, Coalesce, Dagster and Prefect (which handle broader orchestration and sometimes wrap dbt Core), and Paradime, all of which frequently position themselves relative to dbt's pricing and workflow. dbt Labs' own competitive moat is largely the enormous open-source community and ecosystem around dbt Core -- thousands of community-contributed packages, extensive documentation, a large trained analytics-engineer talent pool, and deep integrations with essentially every major cloud warehouse -- which dbt Cloud monetizes by offering the managed, governed, enterprise-ready version of a workflow many teams already know from the free open-source tool. Notable recent developments include the rollout of AI-assisted features (dbt Copilot) for auto-generating and explaining transformation code, continued build-out of the Semantic Layer to reduce metric definition drift across BI tools, and a 2022 price increase and packaging change that significantly altered how usage-based overage billing works, a topic that has generated substantial third-party commentary from analytics consultancies helping customers manage and forecast their dbt Cloud spend.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '50be4027-11b3-43fe-b1ca-c6caad422481';

