-- ── DDraceNetwork ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Free, open-source cooperative multiplayer racing mod of Teeworlds, where teams of up to 64 players work together through community-made maps.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$DDraceNetwork (DDNet): Free Cooperative Teeworlds Mod$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$DDraceNetwork (DDNet) is a free, open-source cooperative platformer mod of Teeworlds where teams race together through community-built maps.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$DDraceNetwork, almost universally known by its abbreviation DDNet, is a free and open-source cooperative multiplayer platformer game built as a modification of Teeworlds, the 2D retro-styled action shooter originally released in 2007. Unlike Teeworlds' standard deathmatch modes, DDNet's core gameplay -- inherited from an earlier community mod called DDRace, short for 'dummy drag race' -- has players work together rather than compete against each other, cooperatively navigating physics-based obstacle courses ('maps') with grappling hooks, hammers, and other Teeworlds tools, often in teams of up to 64 simultaneous players on a single server. DDRace itself was originally developed by a modder known as 3DA, building on an earlier Teeworlds variant called [N]Race, and was maintained through much of its early life by a community figure known as GreyFox; a server-hosting community called DDraceMax (DDmaX) ran a popular version of DDRace from around 2009 to 2014. DDNet emerged on July 17, 2013, when community members -- including a mapper known as Delo -- began organizing an alternative to DDmaX under the name DDraceNetwork, aiming to provide a more actively maintained, community-governed continuation of the DDRace format as the DDmaX project's momentum slowed. Over the following decade, DDNet grew into the dominant hub of the DDRace community, eventually publishing itself as a standalone, freely downloadable game while retaining full compatibility with Teeworlds' underlying engine, maps, and client-server architecture. The game and its source code are distributed on GitHub under the ddnet organization, released under a permissive open-source license combining BSD and zlib terms consistent with Teeworlds' own long-standing zlib-style licensing, meaning the code is free to inspect, modify, and redistribute, and third-party server operators are free to run their own DDNet-compatible servers and community mods (a well-known example being DDNetPP, a variant adding 'city' and 'block' game modes on top of the base DDNet codebase). DDNet is written primarily in C++ for performance and portability, and official builds are available for Windows, macOS, and Linux, distributed via the DDNet website, Steam, and Linux package repositories (it is packaged, for example, in the FreeBSD ports/games collection as DDNet). There is no company behind DDNet in the traditional sense; it is run entirely as a volunteer, community-driven project, with a small team of long-tenured developers and administrators maintaining the client, server software, matchmaking/ranking infrastructure, and a large library of community-submitted maps that go through a structured testing and release process before being added to the official map pool. Because it is entirely free and has no monetization model -- no in-app purchases, subscriptions, or ads -- DDNet's 'business model' is effectively donation- and volunteer-driven, similar to other long-running open-source games such as Teeworlds itself, OpenTTD, or 0 A.D. Its core differentiators within the wider indie/free multiplayer game landscape are its focus on cooperative rather than competitive play, its very low system requirements (owing to Teeworlds' lightweight 2D engine), its global skill-based ranking and leaderboard system that tracks individual and team completion times across thousands of community maps, and its unusually long-lived, active competitive and social community, including regular map-making contests, integrated Discord and forum communities, and localization into multiple languages beyond English, including German (reflecting Teeworlds' and DDNet's roots in the European indie game modding scene) as well as community-maintained translations into languages such as Russian, French, Portuguese, and others. DDNet's closest competitors and comparators are other free, community-driven multiplayer mods and small indie cooperative platformers, though few occupy exactly the same niche; it is sometimes compared to N++ or other precision-platforming games for its skill-based movement mechanics, and to other Teeworlds mods (such as InstaGib or Gores, another cooperative Teeworlds variant with different physics) for shared lineage, but DDNet is by far the largest and most actively maintained of the Teeworlds-derived cooperative mods, effectively having absorbed and outlived most of its direct rivals. Notable facts include DDNet's status as a rare example of a community game mod that not only survived but effectively became the primary distribution and identity for its genre, its continuous 10+ year development history with regular client and server updates, its Wikidata entry documenting its provenance from Teeworlds and DDRace, and its role as a low-barrier entry point into competitive precision platforming for players who want free, lightweight, cooperative multiplayer gameplay without any purchase, subscription, or account paywall. The DDNet team also runs periodic in-house tournaments and community events, coordinates map-testing cycles where new community submissions are play-tested and rated before entering the official map pool, and maintains public infrastructure statistics and a wiki documenting server rules, movement mechanics, and tooling for mappers. Because the project is entirely community-run, governance decisions -- from which maps get added to the official rotation to which code changes get merged -- happen transparently through GitHub pull requests, forum discussions, and Discord channels, giving DDNet a level of openness about its own development process that is unusual even among open-source games, and one that has helped it retain an unusually stable, long-tenured base of both players and contributors since its founding in 2013.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'acb4633f-9c12-4fe7-abe7-4e2c008d1d04';

