-- ── DealHub CPQ ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$AI-powered configure-price-quote (CPQ) platform that helps B2B sales teams build guided quotes, contracts, and manage subscription billing end to end.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Custom/Quote-based$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$250-350 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Tel Aviv, Israel (with US operations in Austin, Texas)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$DealHub CPQ: AI-Powered Quote-to-Revenue Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$DealHub CPQ is an AI-powered configure-price-quote platform that helps B2B sales teams build guided quotes, contracts, and subscription billing.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$DealHub is a configure-price-quote (CPQ) and quote-to-revenue software platform designed to help business-to-business sales teams configure complex product and pricing combinations, generate accurate quotes and contracts, route them through approval workflows, and manage the resulting subscription billing, all while reducing the revenue leakage and delays that often come from manual, spreadsheet-driven quoting processes. The company was founded in 2014 by Eyal Elbahary, Alon Lubin, and Eyal Orgil, initially operating under the name Valooto before rebranding to DealHub as the product matured; it has since grown into one of the more prominent independent players in the CPQ category, sitting alongside sales enablement and revenue operations software rather than as a feature bolted onto a CRM. DealHub is headquartered in Tel Aviv, Israel, reflecting its origins in the Israeli B2B SaaS ecosystem, while also maintaining significant operations in the United States, with sources citing an Austin, Texas office as part of its go-to-market presence; employee counts from various data providers place the company at roughly 250 to 320 people as of 2026, and it has raised total funding reported around $84.5 million to reach an estimated $61.6 million in annual recurring revenue as of 2024 figures cited by industry trackers, positioning it as a well-funded, growth-stage independent vendor rather than a newly launched startup. Architecturally, DealHub is built as a no-code configuration platform: sales operations teams and administrators build out product catalogs, pricing rules, discount guardrails, and approval logic through a visual interface rather than requiring custom development, and the resulting guided-selling playbooks walk sales reps through structured, error-resistant quote creation even for complex, multi-product or multi-dimensional pricing scenarios (including usage-based, tiered, and fixed pricing models combined within a single deal). A central feature of DealHub's platform is its 'DealRoom,' an interactive, collaborative digital space where buyers and sellers can review proposals, negotiate terms, exchange documents, and finalize contracts together, aiming to compress the back-and-forth of traditional PDF-and-email-based deal cycles into a single shared workspace; more recently, DealHub has layered AI features on top of this workflow, positioning the product as an 'AI-powered CPQ, Subscriptions & Usage Billing' platform that can help generate quote language, suggest pricing, and streamline approval routing. The DealHub API connects the CPQ engine to CRMs (most commonly Salesforce and Microsoft Dynamics), ERPs, and e-commerce platforms, allowing quote and contract data to flow automatically into downstream billing and revenue recognition systems, which is central to DealHub's positioning as covering the full 'quote-to-revenue' lifecycle rather than quoting in isolation. Commercially, DealHub does not publish list pricing on its website; all of its packages -- described in the market as CPQ+, CPQ plus Contract Lifecycle Management (CLM), and a full Quote-to-Revenue bundle -- require a custom quote from DealHub's sales team, with third-party pricing analyses estimating typical starting costs in the range of roughly $500 to $1,000 per month depending on team size, modules, and integrations selected, though DealHub explicitly avoids traditional named tiers like 'Basic/Professional/Enterprise' in favor of modular, needs-based packaging. This pricing opacity is typical of CPQ software generally, since deal complexity, seat counts, integration requirements, and support levels vary enormously between a 20-person sales team and a global enterprise; DealHub's target customers skew toward mid-market and enterprise B2B software and technology companies with non-trivial pricing complexity -- multi-product bundles, usage-based components, renewal and upsell motions -- where a spreadsheet or a CRM's native quoting tools become error-prone or slow. DealHub's principal competitors span both dedicated CPQ vendors and adjacent document/proposal tools: Salesforce CPQ (formerly Steelbrick) holds significant market share as the default choice for organizations already deep in the Salesforce ecosystem; Oracle CPQ serves large enterprises with especially complex configuration needs; PandaDoc offers a lighter-weight CPQ module bundled with its broader document workflow and e-signature product, generally aimed at simpler quoting needs than DealHub's guided-selling approach; and other named competitors in analyst and review-site comparisons include Conga, Seismic, Showpad, and Highspot, though the latter three are more accurately sales enablement platforms that overlap with DealHub's DealRoom concept rather than pure CPQ competitors. DealHub differentiates itself from Salesforce CPQ and Oracle CPQ specifically by emphasizing faster implementation timelines and a no-code administration model that doesn't require dedicated Salesforce development resources to maintain pricing logic, and it differentiates from lighter tools like PandaDoc by offering deeper native support for complex, multi-dimensional pricing and subscription billing rather than primarily document generation. Reviews on G2, Gartner Peer Insights, and Capterra generally highlight DealHub's ease of administration and the DealRoom buyer-experience feature as standout strengths, while noting that, as with most CPQ software, initial setup of product catalogs and pricing rules requires meaningful upfront configuration work regardless of the platform's no-code claims. Notable facts include the company's rebrand from Valooto, its consistent positioning around 'guided selling' as a category term it has helped popularize, and its expansion beyond pure CPQ into contract lifecycle management and recurring revenue/subscription billing, reflecting a broader industry trend of CPQ vendors expanding into adjacent quote-to-cash functionality to increase deal size and reduce the number of point solutions a revenue organization needs to stitch together.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '67e99a7f-6ac4-41d8-bead-00bd3c3b6aaa';

