-- ── Debezium ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Open-source distributed platform for change data capture (CDC) that streams row-level database changes in real time via Apache Kafka Connect.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2016, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Debezium: Open-Source Change Data Capture Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Debezium is an open-source change data capture (CDC) platform that streams real-time row-level database changes through Apache Kafka Connect.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Debezium is an open-source distributed platform for change data capture (CDC), a technique for detecting and streaming row-level changes -- inserts, updates, and deletes -- out of a database in near real time so that other systems can react to them without polling or batch extraction. The project was started in 2015-2016 by Randall Hauch, a software engineer at Red Hat, who initiated it as an internal effort to build reliable, low-latency CDC connectors on top of Apache Kafka Connect, addressing a gap in the data infrastructure ecosystem where existing CDC tools were either proprietary, database-vendor-specific, or difficult to operate at scale. Debezium quickly grew from a Red Hat-incubated project into one of the most widely used pieces of open-source data infrastructure in the Kafka ecosystem, supported for years as part of Red Hat Integration and Red Hat's AMQ Streams Kafka distribution, and more recently the project announced a transition of its governance to the Commonhaus Foundation, a vendor-neutral home for open-source projects, reflecting Debezium's maturation into critical infrastructure that benefits from governance independent of any single commercial sponsor. The project is licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0, a permissive license that allows free commercial use, modification, and redistribution with minimal restrictions, which has been a significant factor in its broad enterprise adoption since companies can embed and build on Debezium without copyleft licensing concerns. Architecturally, Debezium works by reading a source database's internal transaction or replication log -- for example, MySQL's binlog, PostgreSQL's logical replication/WAL, MongoDB's oplog/change streams, or SQL Server's CDC tables -- rather than issuing queries against the live database, which means it captures changes with minimal performance impact on the source system and, critically, captures every change in the exact order it occurred, including deletes, which naive polling-based approaches often miss or handle incorrectly. Each supported database has a dedicated Debezium connector that runs inside a Kafka Connect cluster and converts captured changes into a structured event stream published to Kafka topics, where downstream consumers -- microservices, search indexes like Elasticsearch, caches, data warehouses, or other databases -- can subscribe to a continuously updated feed of exactly what changed and when. Beyond individual database connectors, the broader Debezium ecosystem includes Debezium Server, a standalone runtime for streaming captured changes to non-Kafka destinations such as Amazon Kinesis, Google Pub/Sub, Apache Pulsar, or Redis without requiring a full Kafka Connect deployment; and more recently, the Debezium Platform (announced in a 2025 blog post), a management layer aimed at simplifying the deployment, monitoring, and operational lifecycle of Debezium pipelines, addressing longstanding feedback that raw Kafka Connect configuration was a significant operational burden for teams adopting CDC. Debezium's key differentiators relative to alternative CDC approaches include its log-based (rather than query-based or trigger-based) capture mechanism, which avoids the write-amplification and latency problems associated with database triggers and the missed-delete and load problems associated with polling; its broad database support spanning MySQL, PostgreSQL, MongoDB, SQL Server, Oracle, Db2, Cassandra, and Vitess; and its deep native integration with the Kafka ecosystem, which made it the default choice for organizations already running Kafka for event streaming and wanting to extend that same infrastructure to capture database changes. Because Debezium is entirely open-source and free, there is no vendor lock-in or licensing cost, but organizations that want fully managed CDC without operating their own Kafka Connect and Debezium infrastructure typically turn to commercial platforms built either directly on top of Debezium or as CDC alternatives, including Confluent Cloud (which offers managed Debezium-based connectors), Decodable, Redpanda, Estuary Flow, Fivetran, Airbyte, and StreamSets; several of these vendors, including Decodable, explicitly market themselves partly on the basis of taking the operational burden of running Debezium off customers' hands while preserving compatibility with its connector ecosystem. Debezium's target users are data engineers and platform teams building event-driven architectures, real-time analytics pipelines, cache invalidation systems, search index synchronization, database replication and migration tooling, and microservices that need to react to data changes without tightly coupling to the source database's internal schema or polling cadence. Notable facts include Debezium's role as one of the most-cited reference implementations of the CDC pattern in data engineering literature and conference talks (largely due to the visibility of project lead Gunnar Morling, a well-known figure in the Java and data engineering community who has driven much of Debezium's public technical content and, more recently, its governance transition), its continued active release cadence with regular point releases through 2025 and into 2026, and its foundational role in popularizing the 'outbox pattern' and event-driven microservices architectures built on reliable database change streams rather than dual-write or distributed-transaction approaches that are notoriously error-prone in distributed systems. Debezium is frequently taught and referenced in data engineering courses, conference talks at events like Kafka Summit and Devoxx, and vendor documentation across the streaming-data ecosystem, and many downstream projects -- including Kafka-based ETL frameworks, stream-processing engines, and data lake ingestion tools -- ship built-in support for consuming Debezium-formatted change events, treating its event schema as a de facto standard for representing database change data in JSON or Avro form.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '8fe9ecc9-4076-431c-b5a3-fbde13581137';

