-- ── DebOps ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Free, open-source collection of Ansible roles and playbooks for automating the setup of secure, production-ready Debian and Ubuntu infrastructure.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$DebOps: Open-Source Ansible Debian Automation Suite$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$DebOps is a free, open-source collection of Ansible roles and playbooks for automating secure, production-ready Debian and Ubuntu infrastructure.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$DebOps is a free, open-source collection of Ansible roles and playbooks designed to bootstrap and manage IT infrastructure built on Debian or Ubuntu Linux, positioning itself with the tagline of providing 'your Debian-based data center in a box.' The project was founded in October 2013 by Maciej Delmanowski, a Polish system administrator, who built it to codify a consistent, reusable, and security-conscious set of automation building blocks for the kinds of services system administrators repeatedly need to stand up -- web servers, databases, mail systems, DNS, monitoring, and more -- rather than having every team reinvent bespoke Ansible playbooks from scratch. DebOps is distributed under the GNU General Public License version 3 or later (GPL-3.0-or-later), a strong copyleft open-source license that guarantees the code and any distributed modifications remain free and open, consistent with the Debian project's own strong free-software ethos which DebOps deliberately mirrors and extends into the infrastructure-automation layer. Architecturally, DebOps is built entirely on top of Ansible, a widely used agentless configuration management tool that connects to target hosts over SSH and applies declarative YAML-defined state; DebOps does not replace or compete with Ansible itself, but instead ships as a large, curated library of more than 128 individually documented and independently usable Ansible roles covering an unusually broad swath of data center and server needs, including SQL databases (PostgreSQL, MariaDB/MySQL), NoSQL databases, web servers (Nginx, Apache), programming language runtimes, DNS servers, mail transfer agents, monitoring and logging systems, and virtualization technologies such as KVM/libvirt, Docker, and LXC containers. Each role is written with heavy customization in mind, exposing its behavior through Ansible inventory variables so that the exact same role and playbook code can be reused across development, staging, and production environments, or across entirely different organizations, while producing different concrete configurations depending on the inventory values supplied -- a design philosophy that treats infrastructure code the same way software engineers treat reusable libraries, rather than one-off scripts tied to a single environment. DebOps also introduces the concept of 'project directories,' self-contained folders that each bundle their own Ansible inventory alongside custom playbooks, roles, and supporting resources, which lets a single administrator or team maintain multiple independent DebOps-managed environments (for example, separate directories for a company's production cluster, a client's staging environment, and a personal home server) without those environments' configurations interfering with each other, all while drawing on the same shared upstream role library. Because DebOps is purely a community open-source project rather than a commercial product, there is no company, formal headquarters, pricing plan, or vendor support contract behind it; users interact with the project through its documentation site at docs.debops.org, its GitHub organization, and community channels, and installation is done via standard Python packaging (the debops command-line tool is distributed on PyPI) combined with the underlying Ansible roles pulled from the DebOps GitHub repositories. DebOps's target users are systems administrators, DevOps engineers, and infrastructure teams who have standardized on Debian or Ubuntu as their server operating system and want a mature, battle-tested, security-oriented starting point for automating that infrastructure rather than writing every Ansible role from scratch; it is particularly well suited to small and mid-sized organizations, hosting providers, and individual power users running personal infrastructure (home labs, VPS fleets) who value the depth and breadth of the pre-built role library and the strong security defaults baked into roles by a community that overlaps significantly with the Debian project's own contributor base. In the broader infrastructure-as-code and configuration-management landscape, DebOps is best understood not as a competitor to Ansible, Terraform, Puppet, Chef, or Salt at the tooling layer, but as a curated content library that sits on top of Ansible specifically, similar in spirit to how Ansible Galaxy hosts community roles, except DebOps offers a single, internally consistent, well-tested, and interoperable collection maintained under one project's quality bar rather than a marketplace of disparate, independently authored roles of varying quality; the closest comparators are other opinionated Ansible role collections and frameworks such as Ansible Galaxy's more popular individual role authors (e.g., geerlingguy's widely used roles) or larger configuration-management frameworks like Foreman/Katello for Red Hat-family systems, though none replicate DebOps's specific focus on Debian/Ubuntu-first, security-conscious, deeply interoperable role design. Notable facts include the project's remarkably long, continuous maintenance history spanning well over a decade under largely the same founding maintainer, its documentation-first culture (the docs.debops.org site is extensive and versioned alongside releases), and coverage in outlets such as ADMIN Magazine and GNU/Linux Magazine highlighting it as a notable example of community-driven, security-focused infrastructure automation built specifically for the Debian ecosystem rather than as a generic cross-distribution tool. DebOps releases are versioned and tagged in step with its role library, allowing users to pin their infrastructure automation to a specific tested release rather than tracking a constantly moving upstream branch, and the project accepts community contributions of new roles and playbooks through the same GitHub-based review process used by many Debian-adjacent open-source projects, reinforcing its identity as a community commons rather than a single-vendor product.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '0f37df20-288c-490c-8a89-5a00b2c6478e';

